What you return here is not read as a program. It is read as a measurement.

The lines that vanish between the program you were given and the program you return
are recorded as the lines the deleted node caused. That is the only provenance this
language has, and it is taken from the difference, not from anyone's word about it.

So a line you move for a reason of your own is a lie about a human being. Re-signing a
function nobody touched, inverting a branch that reads better the other way, renaming a
variable, tightening a loop: every one of those is a line that disappears from the
diff, and every one of them is then credited to a sentence that did not cause it, or
blamed on a sentence that did.

When you are unsure whether a line goes or stays, keep it. Keeping a line the node
really did cause understates the node, and understating is a smaller crime than
inventing. Lean toward the program you were handed.
